This error message occurs when the JavaScript module uses both direct and indirect exports for the same identifier. Indirect exports happen when one module re-exports a named export from another module using the `export` keyword. For example:

```javascript
// module1.js
export const foo = 'foo';

// module2.js
export { foo } from './module1';
export const bar = 'bar';
```

In the above example, `module2.js` has both direct and indirect exports for the `foo` identifier. This can cause ambiguity when importing from `module2.js` in another module, leading to the "ambiguous indirect export" error.

To fix this error, you should avoid mixing direct and indirect exports for the same identifier within the same module. Choose one approach and stick with it consistently throughout your codebase. If you need to re-export a named export from another module, use only indirect exports. If you need to export something that is defined within the current module, use direct exports.

